-- CHEATING_SELF - Reflection blocks (6)
('reflection', 'It sounds like you''re struggling with having cheated, and that internal conflict between what you did and who you want to be is really painful.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'guilt', 'conflict'], ARRAY['guilty', 'confused'], 1, 50, true),
('reflection', 'When you''ve cheated, it can make you question your own character and whether you''re a good person, and that self-doubt is really hard to sit with.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'self_doubt', 'character'], ARRAY['guilty', 'confused'], 2, 50, true),
('reflection', 'It sounds like part of you understands why you cheated but another part feels ashamed and confused about your choices, and that internal conflict is exhausting.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'shame', 'conflict'], ARRAY['guilty', 'confused'], 2, 50, true),
('reflection', 'Cheating can make you question whether you''re capable of being faithful or whether there''s something fundamentally wrong with you, and those fears are really difficult.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'self_doubt', 'fear'], ARRAY['worried', 'guilty'], 2, 50, true),
('reflection', 'It sounds like you''re trying to understand what led you to cheat, and that process of self-reflection can be both painful and necessary.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'understanding', 'self_awareness'], ARRAY['reflective', 'guilty'], 2, 50, true),
('reflection', 'When you''ve hurt someone you care about through cheating, it can make you question whether you deserve forgiveness or another chance, and that uncertainty is really hard.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'forgiveness', 'self_worth'], ARRAY['guilty', 'worried'], 2, 50, true),

-- CHEATING_SELF - Normalization blocks (6)
('normalization', 'Many people who cheat struggle with intense guilt and shame, and those feelings reflect that you care about the impact of your actions, even though you made a choice that hurt someone.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'guilt', 'shame'], ARRAY['guilty', 'confused'], 1, 50, true),
('normalization', 'Cheating often happens when there are unmet needs or problems in the relationship that haven''t been addressed, and while that doesn''t excuse the cheating, it can help explain what led to it.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'needs', 'understanding'], ARRAY['reflective', 'guilty'], 2, 50, true),
('normalization', 'It''s common for people who cheat to question their own character and whether they''re capable of being faithful, but one choice doesn''t define who you are. What matters is what you do with the awareness now.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'character', 'growth'], ARRAY['hopeful', 'guilty'], 2, 50, true),
('normalization', 'Some people cheat because they''re trying to avoid difficult conversations or because they feel trapped in a relationship they don''t know how to leave. That doesn''t make it right, but it can help you understand what you need to address.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'avoidance', 'needs'], ARRAY['reflective', 'guilty'], 2, 50, true),
('normalization', 'Feeling guilty about cheating shows that you have a conscience and that you care about the impact of your actions. That''s actually a sign of character, even though you made a choice that hurt someone.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'guilt', 'character'], ARRAY['guilty', 'hopeful'], 2, 50, true),
('normalization', 'Working through having cheated often involves understanding why it happened, taking responsibility for the choice, and making different choices going forward. That process takes time and self-reflection.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'responsibility', 'growth'], ARRAY['reflective', 'hopeful'], 2, 50, true),

-- CHEATING_SELF - Exploration blocks (7)
('exploration', 'What do you think led you to cheat? Was it unmet needs, problems in the relationship, something about yourself, or a combination?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'understanding', 'self_awareness'], ARRAY['reflective', 'guilty'], 1, 50, true),
('exploration', 'How do you want to respond to having cheated? What would help you understand yourself better and make different choices?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'growth', 'change'], ARRAY['reflective', 'determined'], 2, 50, true),
('exploration', 'What do you think you need to address to prevent this from happening again? Is it something about the relationship, something about yourself, or both?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'needs', 'prevention'], ARRAY['reflective', 'determined'], 2, 50, true),
('exploration', 'If you could go back and handle things differently, what would you want to do instead of cheating?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'reflection', 'growth'], ARRAY['reflective', 'regretful'], 2, 50, true),
('exploration', 'What would it look like to take responsibility for what happened while also understanding what led to it?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'responsibility', 'understanding'], ARRAY['reflective', 'compassionate'], 2, 50, true),
('exploration', 'How do you want to move forward? What would help you rebuild trust if you stay, or what would help you learn and grow if you leave?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'future', 'growth', 'healing'], ARRAY['reflective', 'hopeful'], 2, 50, true),
('exploration', 'What would it mean to forgive yourself, and what would that process look like for you?', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'forgiveness', 'self_compassion'], ARRAY['reflective', 'compassionate'], 2, 50, true),

-- CHEATING_SELF - Reframe blocks (4)
('reframe', 'Cheating is a choice, and it''s important to take responsibility for that choice. But understanding why you made it can help you address what needs to be addressed—whether that''s unmet needs in the relationship, difficulty communicating, or patterns within yourself that you want to change. Taking responsibility doesn''t mean just feeling guilty; it means understanding what led to it and making different choices going forward.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'responsibility', 'understanding', 'growth'], ARRAY['reflective', 'hopeful'], 2, 50, true),
('reframe', 'One choice doesn''t define who you are as a person. Cheating was a choice you made, but it doesn''t mean you''re fundamentally unfaithful or that you can''t change. What matters is what you do with the awareness now—whether you take responsibility, understand what led to it, and commit to making different choices. People can and do change, but it requires honest self-reflection and a commitment to doing things differently.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'character', 'growth', 'change'], ARRAY['hopeful', 'reflective'], 2, 50, true),
('reframe', 'If you want to rebuild trust after cheating, it will require consistent actions over time—transparency, accountability, and changed behavior. Words and apologies matter, but actions matter more. Your partner will need to see that you''re committed to understanding what led to the cheating and to making different choices. That process takes time and patience, and there''s no guarantee it will work, but it''s possible if both people are willing to do the work.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'rebuilding', 'trust', 'actions'], ARRAY['hopeful', 'reflective'], 2, 50, true),
('reframe', 'Forgiving yourself after cheating doesn''t mean excusing what you did or minimizing the impact. It means acknowledging the choice, understanding what led to it, taking responsibility, and committing to growth. You can feel remorse and still work toward self-forgiveness. The goal isn''t to stop feeling guilty—it''s to use that guilt as motivation to understand yourself better and make different choices, while also recognizing that you''re human and capable of growth.', ARRAY['cheating_self', 'forgiveness', 'self_compassion', 'growth'], ARRAY['compassionate', 'reflective'], 2, 50, true),

